Rapid Project Design Plan                        Transition Meeting and the Project Plan   Information Technology Projects   Fall 2005   Prof. Arthur Goldberg     Computer Science Department, New York University   Summary   Analysis to development transition meeting goals and the content of the Project Plan   Introduction   After an IT project completes, people evaluate it by considering its accomplishments. To achieve significant accomplishments a project must be organized. In particular, I think that an appropriate balance of planning, analysis and design, followed by implementation and deployment, is crucial.  Therefore, we explicitly recognize the transition from the former to the later by holding a ‘Transition meeting’ 1  with our clients.   Development Project   This table summarizes the division of tasks for a Development Project before and after the transition meeting:                               Tasks completed before     the transition meeting                 Tasks     completed after the transition meeting                                Client      relationship                Develop       rapport with the client’s team         Learn       about the client organization         Set       up logistics for communication with client               Business      goals                Learn       about the client’s long term strategic objectives         Collect       ‘wish list’ of features for the project  2                Develop      project specifications                Narrow       down ‘wish list’ to achievable objectives         Write       up project specification                 Clarify       the project’s deliverables         List       problems that could hinder the project (the ‘risks’)               Design                Design       the system’s architecture         Design       the system’s central algorithms         Decide       which tools will be used (evaluate and test tools)               Development      Plan                Plan       the project’s schedule         Enumerate       resources (equipment, software, advice from people) needed to       complete the project         Subdivide       the project’s work into tasks         Allocate       tasks to team members                                     Implementation                Team       members execute implementation tasks         Partial       results communicated to client for feedback               Quality      assurance and testing                Team       members review each other’s code         Team       members writing software unit-test their components       individually         Team       members writing software system-test their components       collectively               [Deployment—not      part of these projects]        [Training—not      part of these projects]        Demo                Present       the system at Projects DemoShow               Delivery                Transfer       all results (documents, code, data, etc.) at the wrap-up       meeting                                          I would like you to write a “Project Plan” which we can discuss at the meeting.   Suggested Outline of an Implementation Project Plan 3 4   This outline contains many of the pieces in the Project Plan for an implementation project. Use only those pieces that are appropriate for your project. I will understand if a few parts are missing because they have not been decided yet.      People        Who is   participating in the project, and what are their roles?          Student team      Client team           Business goals        Summarize the   organization     Why does the   organization want to do this project?     What might the   organization or business gain?          Revenue      Market-share      Decreased costs      Efficiency      Better image      Government    compliance      Risk reduction      Other         What might the   organization or business lose?          Project cost      Opportunity    costs      Other           Requirements: What  should the system do? Should be a detailed list, with perhaps many  items.                Tabulate ‘wish    list’ of features, including, where appropriate            Detailed     description       Requestor’s     name       Importance (as     a function of viewpoint, sometimes)       Difficulty       Category:     functional or other           What other    systems must the system interface with, if any?                 System names     and brief descriptions       Organizations     responsible for the systems       References to     information about these systems       Documentation,     URLs, books and articles, people       Describe how     the interface will probably work           Deliverables            A subset of     the ‘wish list’ of features, which you plan to      actually accomplish in the project. Try to be realistic     about what can be accomplished, given the time and people     available.                Proposed System  Architecture        Components          Their functions      Their interfaces         What technologies   will the project use?              Required and/or    desirable tools            OS(es)       Language(s)       Development     environments       Other           Briefly, why are    these tools appropriate?      References to    information about these tools      Briefly,    tradeoffs between tool choice, if a choice is possible         Draft detailed   designs          Algorithms      Data structures      Protocols      User interfaces            Mockups usually     helpful       Document     agreement between users and business managers, and development     team              Test plan       Development Plan        List project   risks. For each risk          What might go    wrong?      How might the    risk be mitigated?         Important open   issues     Resources          A list of the    resources you'll need (computers, software, reports, data) to    accomplish the deliverables. Describe how they'll be provided.         Enumerate   tasks—break the project into at least as many tasks at team   members          Describe the    task      Estimate the    effort involved in each task. At this point, the actual effort    may range between 50% and 200% of the estimate.         Schedule          A weekly    schedule for the accomplishment of tasks leading to the    deliverables.              Individual   responsibilities          An allocation of    the tasks among the students. For example, Robert will write the    schema, and Samantha will load the data. Allocate tasks according    to interest and skill. Try to divide tasks so each person can    make significant progress independently, that is, without having    to talk to someone else for a while. This speeds progress.      Read      all available documentation        Try      to obtain independent evaluations (perhaps Gartner or      similar—ask me)        Try      to obtain in-person demos        Try      to obtain feedback from existing customers        Prepare      comparison matrix             Plan     deployment, if time allows              Data      conversion        Switch      over        Training             [Deployment—not     part of these projects]       [Training—not     part of these projects]       Demo              Present      the comparison matrix at Projects DemoShow; possibly demo      evaluation copy of selected product             Delivery              Transfer      all results (documents, code, data, etc.) at the wrap-up meeting                           Suggested Outline of an Acquisition Project Plan   This outline contains many of the pieces in the Project Plan for an implementation project. (An project will differ somewhat.) Use only those pieces that are appropriate for your project. I will understand if a few parts are missing because they have not been decided yet.      People        Who is   participating in the project, and what are their roles?          Student team      Client team           Business goals        Summarize the   organization     Why does the   organization want to acquire some system?          What business    process(es) would the system service?      What existing    systems would the acquisition replace, if any?         What might the   organization or business gain?          Increased    revenue      Market-share      Decreased costs      Higher    efficiency      Better image      Government    compliance      Reduced risks      Other         What might the   organization or business lose?          System cost      Opportunity    costs      Transition or    switching costs      Costs of    inadequate performance of an acquired system           Requirements: What  should the system do? Should be a detailed list, with perhaps many  items.           Tabulate ‘wish   list’ of features, including, where appropriate          Detailed    description      Requestor’s    name      Importance (as a    function of viewpoint, sometimes)            E.g., Required,     desirable, necessary in x years, unnecessary           Difficulty      Category:    functional or other         What other   systems must the system interface with, if any?              System names and    brief descriptions      Organizations    responsible for the systems      References to    information about these systems      Documentation,    URLs, books and articles, people      Describe how the    interface will probably work           Candidate systems        List   comprehensively          For each system,    include            Name       Vendor       Price       Functionality     (briefly summarized)       Number of users     and installations       Vendor’s     status       Whether the     systems warrants further investigation, and why                Plan for review,  evaluation and selection        Data collection          For systems that    warrant further investigation, identify a subset of these actions    to pursue            Review system     documentation       Obtain third     party reviews of system – sources include              Trade press        Current      customers        Technology      analysis firms like Gartner             Communicate     with vendor’s sales staff       View a vendor’s     demonstration       Evaluate a     trial use           Plan for further    collection of client requirements, if necessary         Project plan          List    deliverables            Which of the     following will be provided?              Comparison      matrix        Running test      software        Vendor’s      demonstration                 List project    risks. For each risk            What might go     wrong?       How might the     risk be mitigated?           Enumerate    tasks—break the project into at least as many tasks at team    members            Describe the     task       Estimate the     effort involved in each task. At this point, the actual effort     may range between 50% and 200% of the estimate.           Schedule            A weekly     schedule for the accomplishment of tasks leading to the     deliverables.                 Individual    responsibilities            An allocation     of the tasks among the students. For example, Robert will     contact vendors A to L, and Samantha will contact vendors M to Z.      Allocate tasks according to interest and skill. Try to divide     tasks so each person can make significant progress independently,     that is, without having to talk to someone else for a while.      This speeds progress.              Plan for   selection of ‘winning’ system          How will    decision be made?      What input will    be needed?           Demo plans for the  DemoShow     Transition Meeting Agenda                                  Students present analysis report (each student presents their     work)                 45 to 60 min                         All discuss proposed plan; hopefully achieve     consensus                 30 to 45 min                         All discuss availability of resources                 5 min                         Discuss allocation of responsibilities among     students and client                 5 min                         Discuss proposed DemoShow presentation                 10 min                        1   This meeting will be like the “Planning Checkpoint Review”  in Steve McConnell's Software Project Survival Guide (Microsoft  Press, 1998, ISBN: 1-57231-621-7  http://www.construx.com/survivalguide/). Some of the ideas come  from McConnell's “Agenda for the Planning Checkpoint Review”,  http://www.construx.com/survivalguide/checkpointagenda.htm.        2    Obtained by: interviewing concerned parties (users,  management), dreaming up features, analyzing the competition or  other methods.        3   See http://www.cs.nyu.edu/artg/itp/ExampleTransitionReports/   for some example project plans. Note that some projects involve  developing software, whereas others involve evaluating software to  be purchased.        4    For an interesting reference on project planning and  management see the New York State Office for Technology's Project  Management Guidebook, at  http://www.oft.state.ny.us/pmmp/guidebook2/index.htm. New York  State requires that companies who write software for the state to  follow these guidelines.

Rapid Project Design Plan                        Transition Meeting and the Project Plan   Information Technology Projects   Fall 2005   Prof. Arthur Goldberg     Computer Science Department, New York University   Summary   Analysis to development transition meeting goals and the content of the Project Plan   Introduction   After an IT project completes, people evaluate it by considering its accomplishments. To achieve significant accomplishments a project must be organized. In particular, I think that an appropriate balance of planning, analysis and design, followed by implementation and deployment, is crucial.  Therefore, we explicitly recognize the transition from the former to the later by holding a ‘Transition meeting’ 1  with our clients.   Development Project   This table summarizes the division of tasks for a Development Project before and after the transition meeting:                               Tasks completed before     the transition meeting                 Tasks     completed after the transition meeting                                Client      relationship                Develop       rapport with the client’s team         Learn       about the client organization         Set       up logistics for communication with client               Business      goals                Learn       about the client’s long term strategic objectives         Collect       ‘wish list’ of features for the project  2                Develop      project specifications                Narrow       down ‘wish list’ to achievable objectives         Write       up project specification                 Clarify       the project’s deliverables         List       problems that could hinder the project (the ‘risks’)               Design                Design       the system’s architecture         Design       the system’s central algorithms         Decide       which tools will be used (evaluate and test tools)               Development      Plan                Plan       the project’s schedule         Enumerate       resources (equipment, software, advice from people) needed to       complete the project         Subdivide       the project’s work into tasks         Allocate       tasks to team members                                     Implementation                Team       members execute implementation tasks         Partial       results communicated to client for feedback               Quality      assurance and testing                Team       members review each other’s code         Team       members writing software unit-test their components       individually         Team       members writing software system-test their components       collectively               [Deployment—not      part of these projects]        [Training—not      part of these projects]        Demo                Present       the system at Projects DemoShow               Delivery                Transfer       all results (documents, code, data, etc.) at the wrap-up       meeting                                          I would like you to write a “Project Plan” which we can discuss at the meeting.   Suggested Outline of an Implementation Project Plan 3 4   This outline contains many of the pieces in the Project Plan for an implementation project. Use only those pieces that are appropriate for your project. I will understand if a few parts are missing because they have not been decided yet.      People        Who is   participating in the project, and what are their roles?          Student team      Client team           Business goals        Summarize the   organization     Why does the   organization want to do this project?     What might the   organization or business gain?          Revenue      Market-share      Decreased costs      Efficiency      Better image      Government    compliance      Risk reduction      Other         What might the   organization or business lose?          Project cost      Opportunity    costs      Other           Requirements: What  should the system do? Should be a detailed list, with perhaps many  items.                Tabulate ‘wish    list’ of features, including, where appropriate            Detailed     description       Requestor’s     name       Importance (as     a function of viewpoint, sometimes)       Difficulty       Category:     functional or other           What other    systems must the system interface with, if any?                 System names     and brief descriptions       Organizations     responsible for the systems       References to     information about these systems       Documentation,     URLs, books and articles, people       Describe how     the interface will probably work           Deliverables            A subset of     the ‘wish list’ of features, which you plan to      actually accomplish in the project. Try to be realistic     about what can be accomplished, given the time and people     available.                Proposed System  Architecture        Components          Their functions      Their interfaces         What technologies   will the project use?              Required and/or    desirable tools            OS(es)       Language(s)       Development     environments       Other           Briefly, why are    these tools appropriate?      References to    information about these tools      Briefly,    tradeoffs between tool choice, if a choice is possible         Draft detailed   designs          Algorithms      Data structures      Protocols      User interfaces            Mockups usually     helpful       Document     agreement between users and business managers, and development     team              Test plan       Development Plan        List project   risks. For each risk          What might go    wrong?      How might the    risk be mitigated?         Important open   issues     Resources          A list of the    resources you'll need (computers, software, reports, data) to    accomplish the deliverables. Describe how they'll be provided.         Enumerate   tasks—break the project into at least as many tasks at team   members          Describe the    task      Estimate the    effort involved in each task. At this point, the actual effort    may range between 50% and 200% of the estimate.         Schedule          A weekly    schedule for the accomplishment of tasks leading to the    deliverables.              Individual   responsibilities          An allocation of    the tasks among the students. For example, Robert will write the    schema, and Samantha will load the data. Allocate tasks according    to interest and skill. Try to divide tasks so each person can    make significant progress independently, that is, without having    to talk to someone else for a while. This speeds progress.      Read      all available documentation        Try      to obtain independent evaluations (perhaps Gartner or      similar—ask me)        Try      to obtain in-person demos        Try      to obtain feedback from existing customers        Prepare      comparison matrix             Plan     deployment, if time allows              Data      conversion        Switch      over        Training             [Deployment—not     part of these projects]       [Training—not     part of these projects]       Demo              Present      the comparison matrix at Projects DemoShow; possibly demo      evaluation copy of selected product             Delivery              Transfer      all results (documents, code, data, etc.) at the wrap-up meeting                           Suggested Outline of an Acquisition Project Plan   This outline contains many of the pieces in the Project Plan for an implementation project. (An project will differ somewhat.) Use only those pieces that are appropriate for your project. I will understand if a few parts are missing because they have not been decided yet.      People        Who is   participating in the project, and what are their roles?          Student team      Client team           Business goals        Summarize the   organization     Why does the   organization want to acquire some system?          What business    process(es) would the system service?      What existing    systems would the acquisition replace, if any?         What might the   organization or business gain?          Increased    revenue      Market-share      Decreased costs      Higher    efficiency      Better image      Government    compliance      Reduced risks      Other         What might the   organization or business lose?          System cost      Opportunity    costs      Transition or    switching costs      Costs of    inadequate performance of an acquired system           Requirements: What  should the system do? Should be a detailed list, with perhaps many  items.           Tabulate ‘wish   list’ of features, including, where appropriate          Detailed    description      Requestor’s    name      Importance (as a    function of viewpoint, sometimes)            E.g., Required,     desirable, necessary in x years, unnecessary           Difficulty      Category:    functional or other         What other   systems must the system interface with, if any?              System names and    brief descriptions      Organizations    responsible for the systems      References to    information about these systems      Documentation,    URLs, books and articles, people      Describe how the    interface will probably work           Candidate systems        List   comprehensively          For each system,    include            Name       Vendor       Price       Functionality     (briefly summarized)       Number of users     and installations       Vendor’s     status       Whether the     systems warrants further investigation, and why                Plan for review,  evaluation and selection        Data collection          For systems that    warrant further investigation, identify a subset of these actions    to pursue            Review system     documentation       Obtain third     party reviews of system – sources include              Trade press        Current      customers        Technology      analysis firms like Gartner             Communicate     with vendor’s sales staff       View a vendor’s     demonstration       Evaluate a     trial use           Plan for further    collection of client requirements, if necessary         Project plan          List    deliverables            Which of the     following will be provided?              Comparison      matrix        Running test      software        Vendor’s      demonstration                 List project    risks. For each risk            What might go     wrong?       How might the     risk be mitigated?           Enumerate    tasks—break the project into at least as many tasks at team    members            Describe the     task       Estimate the     effort involved in each task. At this point, the actual effort     may range between 50% and 200% of the estimate.           Schedule            A weekly     schedule for the accomplishment of tasks leading to the     deliverables.                 Individual    responsibilities            An allocation     of the tasks among the students. For example, Robert will     contact vendors A to L, and Samantha will contact vendors M to Z.      Allocate tasks according to interest and skill. Try to divide     tasks so each person can make significant progress independently,     that is, without having to talk to someone else for a while.      This speeds progress.              Plan for   selection of ‘winning’ system          How will    decision be made?      What input will    be needed?           Demo plans for the  DemoShow     Transition Meeting Agenda                                  Students present analysis report (each student presents their     work)                 45 to 60 min                         All discuss proposed plan; hopefully achieve     consensus                 30 to 45 min                         All discuss availability of resources                 5 min                         Discuss allocation of responsibilities among     students and client                 5 min                         Discuss proposed DemoShow presentation                 10 min                        1   This meeting will be like the “Planning Checkpoint Review”  in Steve McConnell's Software Project Survival Guide (Microsoft  Press, 1998, ISBN: 1-57231-621-7  http://www.construx.com/survivalguide/). Some of the ideas come  from McConnell's “Agenda for the Planning Checkpoint Review”,  http://www.construx.com/survivalguide/checkpointagenda.htm.        2    Obtained by: interviewing concerned parties (users,  management), dreaming up features, analyzing the competition or  other methods.        3   See http://www.cs.nyu.edu/artg/itp/ExampleTransitionReports/   for some example project plans. Note that some projects involve  developing software, whereas others involve evaluating software to  be purchased.        4    For an interesting reference on project planning and  management see the New York State Office for Technology's Project  Management Guidebook, at  http://www.oft.state.ny.us/pmmp/guidebook2/index.htm. New York  State requires that companies who write software for the state to  follow these guidelines.
